unittitle.value: Study of Chronic Marihuana Users in Jamaica (The Ganja Study)

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: The Study of Chronic Marihuana Users in Jamaica (The Ganja Project) is a collection of materials relating to an anthropological and medical study of the long-term effects of cannabis smoking. It was commissioned by the National Institute of Mental Health in 1970 and conducted by the Research Institute for the Study of Man, in collaboration with the University of the West Indies, between 1970 and 1972. Materials include human subject data, background research on the physiological and psychological effects of cannabis use, the legal issues surrounding research involving controlled substances, and published materials relating to the study.

p.value:
Additionally, please note that this collection is stored 
                <extref ns2:href="http://www.nyu.edu/library/bobst/research/arch/ganja.htm">
                    <archref> offsite </archref> </extref>, and you must contact the repository to schedule access.

Published citations should take the following form:
                <lb/>
                <lb/>Identification of item, date (if known); The Research Institute for the Study of Man: Study of Chronic Marihuana Users in Jamaica (The Ganja Project); RISM RG 12; box number; folder number; 
                <address>
                    <addressline>New York University;</addressline>
                    <addressline>New York University</addressline>
                </address>

<list>
                    <item>Rubin, Vera, and Lambros Comitas. 
                        <emph render="italic">Ganja in Jamaica: A Medical Anthropological Study of Chronric Marihuana Use</emph>. The Hague and Paris: Mouton & Co., 1975.</item>
                </list>

The bulk of the collection consists of human subject data from medical analyses conducted in 1970. There exists a substantial amount of background research material for the study relating to existing research on the effects of cannabis smoking and other drug use. Other background research includes an assessment of the legal status of marihuana use in Jamaica, which was produced for the study, and materials examining the legal issues related to clinical studies involving illegal substances. This research includes pamphlets from groups such as NORML and nearly two years of issues of 
                <emph render="italic">The U.S. Journal of Drug and Alcohol Dependence</emph>. Also included are press clippings, book reviews, magazines, and journals with content relating to the published results of the Study of Chronic Marihuana Users in Jamaica, as well as the final report as issued to the National Institute of Mental Health. Data from the ethnographic study of Jamaican communities are not part of The Ganja Project collection.
